Doneeka Hodges shot 6-for-8 from 3-point
range and finished with 24 points as Louisiana State (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) 
stretched its winning streak to 15 games with an 82-39 victory over
Kentucky on Thursday night.
article.headline: Gunter earns 400th victory at LSU
article.linkText: No. 3 LSU rolls by Kentucky to win 15th straight
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Doneeka Hodges snapped out of her
shooting slump in time for Louisiana State to cruise to victory.

	   Hodges, who averaged just 7.6 points, shot 6-for-8 from 3-point
range and finished with 24 points as LSU (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today, No. 2 AP) beat Kentucky 82-39 on
Thursday night to stretch its winning streak to 15.

	   "I've been struggling shooting the ball,'' Hodges said. "I
don't know what happened, it was just falling for me.''

	   LSU (15-0, 3-0 Southeastern Conference) matched the school
record for longest winning streak -- set in the 1995-96 season -- and
got off to its best start ever. It was also the biggest margin of
victory in an SEC game for the Tigers, who are off to a 3-0 start
in the conference for the third time.

	   The victory was the 666th for coach Sue Gunter, and her 400th in
21 seasons at LSU.

	   "It's great to have an experienced team that can handle all the
hoopla around this,'' Gunter said.

	   Seimone Augustus scored 16 for LSU, and DeTrina White added 10.

	   Kentucky (8-6, 1-1) had won five of its last six, but hasn't won
on the road this season. Jenny Pfeiffer and Shambrica Jones each
scored nine points against the Tigers' stifling defense, which held
the Wildcats to 30 percent shooting.

	   "I think that it is always the goal for us to come out and try
to stop teams from what they're good at,'' Hodges said. "In order
to do that, we have to play good defense and disrupt their
offense.''

	   LSU, which has allowed just two opponents to score more than 60
points, ranks first in the nation in points allowed at 50.5, just
ahead of Connecticut's 50.6. They're also ninth in blocked shots at
nearly six per game and 13th in field-goal percentage defense at 35
percent.

	   "We went to ball screens and they jumped out in front of us,''
Kentucky guard Rita Adams said. "They brought a lot of pressure on
us and we didn't screen good enough to get around their traps.''

	   The Tigers made quick work of the Wildcats, jumping out to a 6-0
lead, then went on a 35-14 run in which Kentucky made only one foul
shot during a three-minute stretch.

	   "They have great athleticism and great shooters on the floor,''
Kentucky coach Bernadette Mattox said. "I can't say enough about
their team.''

	   LSU had only three turnovers in the first half and led 53-21 at
halftime.

	   Kentucky had 26 turnovers, including 18 on steals by LSU. The
Tigers scored 29 points off turnovers.
